# Creating .gitkeep Files

Git doesn't track empty directories. To preserve folder structure, create empty `.gitkeep` files:

## Commands

### Linux/Mac
```bash
# Create directories with .gitkeep
mkdir -p outputs static
touch outputs/.gitkeep
touch static/.gitkeep
```

### Windows (PowerShell)
```powershell
# Create directories with .gitkeep
New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force -Path outputs
New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force -Path static
New-Item -ItemType File -Path outputs\.gitkeep
New-Item -ItemType File -Path static\.gitkeep
```

### Windows (Command Prompt)
```cmd
mkdir outputs
mkdir static
type nul > outputs\.gitkeep
type nul > static\.gitkeep
```

## Folder Structure After
```
ai-image-generator/
├── outputs/
│   └── .gitkeep          ← Empty placeholder
└── static/
    └── .gitkeep          ← Empty placeholder
```

## Why?
- Git only tracks **files**, not **folders**
- `.gitkeep` preserves folder structure in repository
- Convention name (could be any name, but `.gitkeep` is standard)
- When you generate images, they go in `outputs/` (but aren't committed due to `.gitignore`)